Tried something new this past Sunday at @goddessegyptblaqueknyle Bare Bottom Burlesque Brunch. An act I created, in my bedroom, during lockdown got to be done in person. Not only was the act new BUT the movements were too. It was kinda like my own take on modern/lyrical dance. Forms of dance I’ve always admired and wanted to dive deeper into (I watch videos on social media all the time). 

Not sure if I’ve mentioned this before but I’m definitely not a trained dancer. I didn’t start taking dance classes until I went to college. I’ve always loved dance and have loved to dance since I was a kid. My parents never but me in classes as a kid so instead I just watched a lot of music videos and tried copying what I saw 🤷🏾‍♀️

Anyone, moral of the story, lol…just dance…let the music take you…..you’re never too old to learn different things annnnnd burlesque comes in all forms

Oh man! This has been quite an epic year. It had its trials and tribulations but regardless I powered through and worked on overcoming a serious injury to back to doing the things I love. 

I remember sitting in the ER crying and feeling like my life was over. I know idea what 2022 has in-store for me. I entered the year, being able to put on two shoes, which enabled me to perform barefoot. Eventually, I put on my dance shoes and my skates AND got to bust out my passport! I travelled to three countries…got to headline a run at the iconic @windmillsoho, spent time with my favourite people in the entire world, we brought Tease If You Please @teaseproductions back, I was on a game show, had private gigs, auditioned for Cardi B, did a podcast with one of my fave queens @deltawork , etc. I’m beyond grateful for what the year brought me even though it took some people away and even though my ass got stuck in Canada (however with my friends)

I pray that 2023 keeps bringing opportunities and many more moments and memories with my friends, family and doing the things I love. 

Thank you to all the producers who booked me, for all my family and friends who continued to uplift and support me and to all the followers who ended the year by voting me into the @21stcenturyburlesque top 10 list. May I still be able to make an impact im this world! ❤️

ANNOUNCING: Brown Sugar Burlesque - 2.26.23 - Los Angeles

Brown Sugar is a live burlesque entertainment experience launching in Los Angeles in February 2023. Created in light of similar issues prevalent in the industries of hospitality and burlesque, namely a lack of representation and opportunities, Brown Sugar will create a space that centers and celebrates Black creativity and artistry both onstage and behind the bar.

What will a night at Brown Sugar be like? Sexy. Brown Sugar is a cabaret experience with burlesque at its heart, featuring a predominantly Black cast of performers, musicians and bartenders. The evening will open with live music and cocktails before segueing into a hosted dinner show with two acts. The night closes out with a DJ-led, R&B only, dance party.

#BrownSugarBurlesque is owned and produced by women of color. We are committed to building strong relationships with partners who share our core values and help us make a positive impact. We are excited to explore all potential opportunities to create meaningful partnerships with like-minded organizations, however, priority will be given to inquiries from Black-owned brands, businesses and BIPOC ambassadors/spokespeople.

OUR TEAM:
Paige Walwyn @paigewalwyn is based in Chicago, IL (by way of New Jersey) and heads up our partnerships and sponsor relations.

Veronica Correa @veedotwhat is based in San Diego, CA (by way of NYC) and directs our marketing and social media.

Jessabelle Thunder @jessthndr is based in Los Angeles, CA and has been a burlesque performer and pin-up model for over a decade. Jessabelle produces (and headlines!) our show.

Kendall Buhk @kenniekealohilani is based in Los Angeles, CA (by way of The Bay Area) and leads our event production and logistics.

Mariah Kunkel @mariah.kunkel is currently based in Los Angeles, CA, though she lived and worked in NYC for 13 years. Mariah is the founder of Brown Sugar.

GET INVOLVED:
🤎Give us a follow! @thebrownsugarburlesque
🤎Join our mailing list and be the first to know when tickets drop: http://thebrownsugarburlesque.com (link in bio!)
🤎Want to perform? Volunteer? Sponsor? Email us: info@thebrownsugarburlesque.com

Same costume, new year, new song, new act. Last year, I used this costume and debuted a new act to a song that I absolutely love but every time I did it, something felt off. I couldn’t put my finger on what exactly it was-choreo? Costume? Music? 

“Heart Shaped Box” has been in my “future acts” playlist for years. It wasn’t until I used that song and this costume when I performed for @thescarletopera that I realised that even though I loved my previous song, I just didn’t feel as connected to it. This new song feels very much like me. I think I can truly sit into it. 

When I feel connected to a song I think it shows in my movements, facial expressions and energy and the audience can feel it too. It’s one of the things I teach in my musicality lecture- connecting to your music is key. (Have to listen to my own advice)

Anywho, I had to let go of the old song and I feel like I’ve breathed new life into this silk veil from @gaealady.silkcreatrix and corset by @puimondcorsets Not a fully formed act yet but it’s getting there.

Mediocrity, a topic that’s been on my mind a lot since this Summer. Yes, I have had some feelings about me being mediocre and questioning my life choices but mostly I’ve had this revelation that many people just coast by or are even rewarded for mediocrity while I feel like I have to literally do the most to be seen and heard. It’s upsetting and at times I feel defeated. 

@rynieresponsible sent me the following post the other day at just the right time and it really resonated with me ( by @dangerouswco on twitter): 
Whatever you think you can’t do, just know that there is someone who is confidently doing it wrong right now. They have no plans at doing it better either and people are paying them to do it. Please believe in your own excellence as much as they believe in their mediocrity. 

Believe in my own excellence and continue to focus on myself and my community; not letting someone else’s mediocrity effect me so much. And number one, stop trying to prove myself to people who clearly don’t see how unique and special I may be. (FYI I’m not just talking about the burlesque world. This goes for relationships and all other avenues of my life). 

Thoughts?

October 9th marked 14th effing years of me performing! 14!! I can’t believe it! 14 years and still going. You may ask yourself, as I do often, “Jessabelle? Why after 14 years on this career path do you still say yes to practically every show? To the point where you’re sooooo tired and lacking sleep? Why do you constantly get yourself on a plane only to turn right back around? Whhhhy? Bish! Rest!”

Well….the answer is multi layered. I love to travel and I love what I do but ultimately, after some soul searching, the main answer is because I want to put my Black body and , hopefully, unique style of performing in front of as many different audiences as I possibly can forever and always. I’m here to shift people’s thinking. I’m here to be representation where it may lack. That’s why. 

Thank you all for joining me on my journey via social media and in person 🫶🏾🫶🏾🥹 Thank you to everyone who I’ve met along the way and befriended, who’ve been part of my life. I feel the love often and it’s what also keeps me going. Mad love for you all! 

Speaking of journeys….TOMORROW I’ll be in Montreal, headlining the @montrealburlesquefest produced by @scarlettjamesofficial THEEEEEN SUNDAY it’s our last @thebrownsugarburlesque of the year and it’s not to be missed!

Oh my gosh! What is this life I get the privilege of living! The first burlesk show I ever saw was Forty Deuce in Las Vegas for my 22nd or 23rd birthday. I wanted nothing more than to see the original in LA but my the time I turned 21 it had already closed. Thankfully the Vegas one was open. 

That night, I fell in love with the art form. The live music, the dancing women all over the bar, the energy! I had a thought of wanting to try it but didn’t think it was possible after seeing those ladies tear up the stage. However, from that night on I had to see more burlesque. And….well…here we are in 2023. 

How wild that I had the opportunity to dance on stage with @williemcneilmusic the man, the legend, the icon, who played for so many burlesk ladies that I admired and have now gotten to dance alongside and some I get to call my pals- @djmissdakota @carolinacerisola  and many more. Although I never saw them live at Forty Deuce I saw clips, photos and saw them on other stages. I was captivated and obsessed! 

Thanks to @themissmarquez and her epic @empowermentinheels birthday celebration show, for a night, I got to imagine that I was a Forty Deuce dancer. And a big thanks to @williemcneilmusic accompanied by Jay Works and @mrrustyk 
There’s nothing like dancing with a skilled professional band. And the fact that Willie gets into it too is beyond!!

VOTED #3 MOST INFLUENTIAL BURLESK PERFORMER 2023 via @21stcenturyburlesque by way of those who voted this year! (I’ve been waiting forever to use this sound!!!)

When @rynieresponsible asked me if I was excited about finding out, my response was “that’s not quite the emotion I’m feeling…it’s more like shock” Shocked and very honoured that people thought about me enough to add me to their list of votes this year (and the past four or so for that matter). And so much so, that my name is up there as number three and preceded (is that the word?) by two badass babes who I look up to and can call friends- @gingerleevalentine (no. 2) and @loulouladuchesse (no. 1)

This year has been a whirlwind. Myself and @mariah.kunkel launched @thebrownsugarburlesque here in LA (inspired in part by @itsjeezloueez and @jeezysjukejoint ), I practically lived at the airport, I’ve had some awakenings that I’m forever trying to work on and I’ve been contemplating some life changes and trying to put things into motion. At some point, I even started juggling like four jobs at once. 

Anywho, this has been a great way to wrap up 2023 and a great way to move into 2024 which I hope will be full of more art, more work for the community and the society at large and more travel so I can spread the passion I have to every inch of this planet and make some kind of an impact. 

Thank you to everyone who voted for me! Thank you to @21stcenturyburlesque for compiling this mega list every year. Congratulations to all of those on the list; your hard-work, dedication, contributions and passion for this art-form was seen, is valid and appreciated 🫶🏾

To those not on this list…congratulations! In 2023, your hard-work, dedication, contributions and passion for this art-form was seen, is valid and appreciated 🫶🏾
